 <subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-a-circle">
    <title>Area of a circle</title>
    <p>
      A circle is a closed two-dimensional 
      figure in which the set of all the points in the plane is 
      equidistant from a given point called ‚Äúcentre‚Äù.
    </p>
    <p>
      The diameter of the circle divides it into two equal parts.
    </p>
    <image width="40%">
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}
        % Draw the circle with a very thick pink outline
        \draw[very thick, black] (0,0) circle (2cm);

        % Draw the diameter
        \draw[thick, magenta] (-2,0) -- (2,0);
        
        % Mark the center
        \fill[magenta] (0,0) circle (2pt);

        % Label the diameter
        \node at (0,0.3) {\textbf{Diameter (d)}};
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
      
      
    </image>
    <p>
      <m>{\color{black}\textbf{Circle Formula.}}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Area of a circle is the amount of 
      space occupied by the circle.
    </p>

    <sidebyside>
      <p>
      The circle formula to find the area is given by <m>\text{Area of a circle}= \pi r^2</m> where, 
      <m>r</m> is the radius of 
      the 
      circle and <m>\pi=\frac{22}{7} \,\text{or} \, 3.142 </m>.
    </p>
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image >
      \begin{tikzpicture}
        % Draw the circle
        \filldraw[fill=yellow, draw=purple, thick] (0,0) circle (3);
        
        % Draw the radius
        \draw[thick, magenta] (0,0) -- (3,0);
        
        % Draw the center point
        \filldraw[magenta] (0,0) circle (3pt);
        
        % Label the radius
        \node[anchor=south, black] at (1,0) {\large $r$};
        
        % Label the area formula
        \node[anchor=north west, scale=1.2] at (-1,-1) {\textbf{Area = $\pi \times r^2$}};
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
    </image>
    </sidebyside>

